<h1>LG Washer CE Error Code — Fix It Same Day</h1>

<p>CE on an LG washer is an overcurrent error — the control sees the motor pulling more electrical current than it should and shuts down to protect itself. Sometimes that's just an overloaded or jammed drum forcing the motor to strain; other times it's the motor or control board. Here's how to tell the quick fix from the real repair. Same-day across LA, Orange County and Ventura. Call (323) 990-7550.</p>

<h2>What the CE Code Means</h2>
<p>CE is an overcurrent fault. The control monitors how much current the motor draws, and when that climbs past a safe limit it stops the cycle rather than let the motor or board take the strain. High current means the motor is working harder than it should — either because something is physically resisting the drum, or because the motor or its drive circuit has developed a fault. It's a protective shutdown, not a guaranteed dead motor.</p>

<h2>What Causes a CE Error on an LG Washer</h2>
<p>In order of how often we find it:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>An overloaded drum</strong> — too much laundry forcing the motor to draw more current. The easiest to rule out.</li>
  <li><strong>An item jammed against the drum</strong> that makes the motor strain to turn it.</li>
  <li><strong>A shorted or failing motor winding</strong> drawing excess current.</li>
  <li><strong>A loose motor connector or damaged wiring.</strong></li>
  <li><strong>A control-board fault</strong> in the motor drive circuit.</li>
</ul>

<h2>What You Can Safely Check Yourself First</h2>
<p>Unplug the washer first. If the drum is packed tight, take out part of the load — an overload is the most common easy fix for CE. Then turn the drum by hand and feel for anything jammed where the drum meets the tub, like a stray sock or underwire that makes it strain. Clear what you can reach, plug back in, and power-cycle it. If it runs and CE clears, the load or a jam was the cause.</p>

<h2>When It's the Motor or Control (and What We Do)</h2>
<p>If the load is light, the drum turns freely, and CE keeps returning, the draw is coming from the motor or its drive circuit. Our techs test the motor windings for a short and check the control board's motor drive before replacing anything, so you're not paying for the wrong part. Motor or control-board work runs $300–420 installed depending on which has failed. The $65 diagnostic is waived when we do the repair.</p>

<h2>CE vs Other LG Codes</h2>
<p>CE is overcurrent — the motor drawing too much. LE means the motor is locked and the drum won't turn at all. UE means the drum turns but the load is unbalanced. CE is about how hard the motor is pulling, not whether it can spin, so check the load and for a jam before assuming the worst.</p>

