<h2>Frequently Asked Questions — LG Washer CE Error</h2>

<h3>What does the CE code mean on my LG washer?</h3>
<p>CE means the motor is drawing too much current, so the control shuts down to protect itself. It's an overcurrent fault — often just an overloaded or jammed drum, sometimes a motor or control-board problem — not automatically a dead machine.</p>

<h3>Can I fix an LG washer CE error myself?</h3>
<p>Sometimes. Unplug it, remove part of the load if the drum is packed, and turn the drum by hand to feel for anything jammed against it. Power-cycle and restart; if the motor isn't straining anymore and CE clears, the load or a jam was the cause.</p>

<h3>How much does it cost to fix an LG washer CE error?</h3>
<p>If it's an overload or a stuck object, it's a quick service call with the $65 diagnostic waived when we do a repair. If the motor or control board has failed, that work runs $300–420 installed. We test the windings and board before quoting. We're licensed with the Bureau of Household Goods and Services (#49573).</p>

<h3>Why does my LG washer show CE during the wash or spin?</h3>
<p>That's when the motor works hardest, so an overload, a jam, or a failing winding pushes the current past the limit and trips CE right as the drum tries to turn under load. A loose motor connector does the same. We check the load and the motor's draw before condemning any part.</p>

<h3>Is it safe to keep using my LG washer with a CE error?</h3>
<p>No — repeated restarts on an overcurrent fault stress the motor and control board. Leave it off, lighten the load, and clear any jam; if CE comes back, have the motor and board tested rather than forcing more cycles.</p>

